name: Netsuite ERP 2018 Release 1
description: Add a Netsuite Instance to connect your existing Netsuite account to the ERP Hub, allowing you to manage all of your ERP activities across multiple ERP Elements. You will need your Netsuite account information to add an instance.

configuration.name: Authentication Type
configuration.description: This is a required field. Please select custom for Token Based Authentication or basic for Basic Authentication. If the value is not supplied Basic Authentication will be assumed.

configuration.name: Allow Select Fields parameter
configuration.description: Enables use of global fields query parameter to filter response to only specified fields. This will override any existing vendor functionality on the connector

configuration.name: Connect TO Sandbox
configuration.description: Connect TO Sandbox SET YES TO Sandbox AND NO TO CONNECT TO Production

configuration.name: Account ID
configuration.description: Your account ID. This can be found under Web Services preferences in Netsuite.

configuration.name: App ID
configuration.description: The ID of your application. This can be found under Integration settings in Netsuite.

configuration.name: Enforce Single Session
configuration.description: SET Yes Enforce Single session to Netsuite across the cluster.Since Netsuite does not support concurrency out of the box and has to be purchased as an additional option

configuration.name: Specify Single Session Lock Key
configuration.description: This Key will be used to Lock all instances to ensure only 1 api is executed to Netsuite

configuration.name: Role ID
configuration.description: The NetSuite SSO Role ID. If not provided, defaults to 3

configuration.name: Filter null values from the response
configuration.description: Used to enable/disable filtering of null values from the responses.

configuration.name: Default select fields
configuration.description: Generic map used to specify default fields for bulk download and GET /all requests. Each key should be the canonical objectName and values may be specified as a comma-delimited string or a list of strings

configuration.name: Disable Mandatory CustomField Validation
configuration.description:
If enabled, when data for a custom field
is required for NetSuite UI submissions, it is NOT required when submitting a Web
services request. If not enabled, an error is thrown whenever the data for a required
custom field is not provided.

configuration.name: Event Poller REFRESH INTERVAL
configuration.description: Used FOR how often TO poll the application (IN minutes)

configuration.name: Event Poller Resources Configuration
Callback Notification Signature Key
configuration.description: A key used to generate a validation hash header of the event/bulk notification webhook callback payload

configuration.name: Vendor EVENT TYPE
configuration.description: Netsuite Finance Beta Vendor EVENT TYPE

configuration.name: Subcription ID
configuration.description: Netsuite Finance Beta Vendor Subscription ID

objects.name: folders
objects.description: Records all the folders

objects.name: accounts
objects.description: People or companies that purchase goods and services from your business

objects.name: activities
objects.description: Tasks are activities that need to be completed

objects.name: billingAccounts
objects.description: A billing account shows all billing information for a customer or sub-customer that includes the billing schedule, default payment terms, bill-to address, and currency

objects.name: bills
objects.description: The vendor bill transaction records payables as they arrive from vendors, allowing you to pay bills from the payables list as they are due, and providing an accurate picture of payables at all points of the billing cycle

objects.name: budgets
objects.description: A budget records the expected values of income and expenses for your business.

objects.name: campaigns
objects.description: Campaign records are used to manage your marketing initiatives. With campaign records, you can manage your online marketing as well as your offline efforts. You can create and send email marketing messages, manage paid keywords, send promotions through the mail, and manage your advertising campaigns

objects.name: cases
objects.description: Support Cases are support issues logged for a specific company

objects.name: casesMessages
objects.description: A message is used to record correspondence you have with a specific business

objects.name: checks
objects.description: A check transaction creates and records a check used to pay an expense, records an expense paid in cash and not entered as a bill, or records a non-check debit transaction, such as a debit card transaction, ATM (automated teller machine) transaction, or EFT (electronic funds transfer) payment. A check transaction records an expense directly to your books by debiting the expense account specified in the transaction detail and crediting the bank account the check selected for the check

objects.name: classifications
objects.description: classifies transaction based on accounting preferences and implementation behaviour

objects.name: contacts
objects.description: Contacts represent people or companies that you deal with in the daily activity of your business

objects.name: creditMemos
objects.description: A credit memo is a record of credit due to a customer. Credit memo amounts can be applied toward the charges for specific items and for specific transactions such as invoices

objects.name: creditTerms
objects.description: Terms are used to specify when payment is due on your customers' invoices

objects.name: currencies
objects.description: Lists currencies in ERP system

objects.name: currencyRates
objects.description: Records the currency Rates supported in different countries.

objects.name: customFields
objects.description: Custom fields are fields that you can add to your records and transactions to record information specific to your business needs. Record custom fields can be added to existing and custom subtabs on the entry forms you use to enter records in your NetSuite account. Transaction custom fields can be added to the top (body) or the line items (columns) of transactions

objects.name: customRecordTypes
objects.description: Custom records are record types other than standard NetSuite record types. You can only import custom record data after the custom record type has been created in your account

objects.name: customRecordTypesCustomRecordFields
objects.description: Custom record custom fields can only be set on a custom record after the custom record has been created

objects.name: customRecordTypesCustomRecords
objects.description: Custom record custom fields can only be set on a custom record after the custom record has been created

objects.name: customerRefunds
objects.description: A customer refund is a transaction that records a payment you make to a customer. This payment is generally in the form of currency or a printed check

objects.name: customerStatuses
objects.description: A customer status describes a lead, prospect, or customer's stage in the sales cycle. All statuses have a probability level associated with them. This probability reflects the percentage chance that a lead or prospect will purchase from your business. Leads should have a 0 probability. If the probability increases, they are then considered prospects

objects.name: customers
objects.description: people or companies that purchase goods and services from your business

objects.name: departments
objects.description: Departments are categories that you can create to separate and track records such as financials, transactions, and employees

objects.name: deposits
objects.description: record deposits to your bank accounts to capture customer payments and other monies received in the course of doing business. By recording funds deposited, you can accurately track income

objects.name: employees
objects.description: Employee records store information for contact, login, payroll and human resources purposes

objects.name: estimates
objects.description: An estimate transaction, sometimes referred to as a quote, is a non-posted record of estimated charges to a customer. An estimate can be printed, emailed, or faxed to the customer. After the customer accepts the estimate, it can be converted into a sales order, invoice, or cash sale

objects.name: files
objects.description: Records all the files.

objects.name: foldersFiles
objects.description: Records of all files in a File Cabinet

objects.name: foldersFolders
objects.description: Records of all folders in a File Cabinet

objects.name: inventoryAdjustments
objects.description: The inventory adjustment transaction changes the quantity and value of an inventory item without entering a purchase order

objects.name: inventoryTransfers
objects.description: The Inventory Transfer transaction posts details about per-location item inventory level changes when items are transferred between two locations

objects.name: invoices
objects.description: An invoice is a record of a sale to a customer. Invoicing is the process of creating bills for goods and services that customers receive. Record an invoice when payment is not received at the time of delivery. The invoice amount is the total due to be paid to you by the customer

objects.name: itemReceipts
objects.description: An item receipt transaction records the receipt of returned items from customers.

objects.name: items
objects.description: Items are the goods and services you sell to customers, and the parts and raw materials you purchase from vendors. They can also include line items on sales and purchase forms, like discounts and miscellaneous charges

objects.name: journalEntries
objects.description: Any transaction that changes the balance in a ledger account does so by posting a journal entry

objects.name: leads
objects.description: people or companies that purchase goods and services from your business

objects.name: ledgerAccounts
objects.description: The ledger is a permanent summary of all amounts entered in supporting journals which list individual transactions by date. Every transaction flows from a journal to one or more ledgers. A company's financial statements are generated from summary totals in the ledgers

objects.name: locations
objects.description: The Locations feature enables you to track information about employees and transactions for multiple offices or warehouses

objects.name: lookups
objects.description: Retrieve all possible values for a selection field from the Finance system

objects.name: opportunities
objects.description: Opportunities represent negotiations with prospects

objects.name: opportunitiesActivities
objects.description: Tasks are activities that need to be completed. Use the task record to add new tasks for individuals, companies or contacts and to modify those records

objects.name: paymentMethods
objects.description: Lists ways to make a payment. eg - cash, credit card, debit etc

objects.name: payments
objects.description: When a customer makes a payment, record the payment and apply it to the appropriate invoice or cash sale. Applying a payment decreases the amount due and tracks income

objects.name: payrollItems
objects.description: Payroll items store values for payroll transaction line items

objects.name: phoneCalls
objects.description: Phone calls records are used to document phone call activity. All information submitted for a phone call record is stored on a record in the phone call list, on the customer record who calls and on any contact's records referenced in the call contact list

objects.name: projects
objects.description: Use project records to organize your resources and manage the time required to complete tasks for company projects

objects.name: states
objects.description: Records of all countries

objects.name: transferOrders
objects.description: The Transfer Order transaction is used to move inventory between locations when the Multi-Location Inventory (MLI) feature is enabled.Transfer orders can initialize item fulfillment and item receipt transactions

objects.name: workOrders
objects.description: Work order transactions track the production of assembly items needed for stock or to fill orders. Work orders track the quantities of assemblies that need to be built and the quantities of components, or member items, needed to do so
